#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:322
msgid "``(flexible_dtype, itemsize)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:315
msgid ""
"The first argument must be an object that is converted to a zero-sized "
"flexible data-type object, the second argument is an integer providing the "
"desired itemsize."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:339
msgid "``(fixed_dtype, shape)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:328
msgid ""
"The first argument is any object that can be converted into a fixed-size "
"data-type object. The second argument is the desired shape of this type. If "
"the shape parameter is 1, then the data-type object used to be equivalent to "
"fixed dtype. This behaviour is deprecated since NumPy 1.17 and will raise an "
"error in the future. If *shape* is a tuple, then the new dtype defines a sub-"
"array of the given shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:378
msgid "``[(field_name, field_dtype, field_shape), ...]``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:345
msgid ""
"*obj* should be a list of fields where each field is described by a tuple of "
"length 2 or 3. (Equivalent to the ``descr`` item in the :obj:`~object."
"__array_interface__` attribute.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:349
msgid ""
"The first element, *field_name*, is the field name (if this is ``''`` then a "
"standard field name, ``'f#'``, is assigned).  The field name may also be a 2-"
"tuple of strings where the first string is either a \"title\" (which may be "
"any string or unicode string) or meta-data for the field which can be any "
"object, and the second string is the \"name\" which must be a valid Python "
"identifier."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:356
msgid ""
"The second element, *field_dtype*, can be anything that can be interpreted "
"as a data-type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:359
msgid ""
"The optional third element *field_shape* contains the shape if this field "
"represents an array of the data-type in the second element. Note that a 3-"
"tuple with a third argument equal to 1 is equivalent to a 2-tuple."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:364
msgid ""
"This style does not accept *align* in the :class:`dtype` constructor as it "
"is assumed that all of the memory is accounted for by the array interface "
"description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:370
msgid ""
"Data-type with fields ``big`` (big-endian 32-bit integer) and ``little`` "
"(little-endian 32-bit integer):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:375
msgid ""
"Data-type with fields ``R``, ``G``, ``B``, ``A``, each being an unsigned 8-"
"bit integer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:422
msgid ""
"``{'names': ..., 'formats': ..., 'offsets': ..., 'titles': ..., "
"'itemsize': ...}``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:384
msgid ""
"This style has two required and three optional keys.  The *names* and "
"*formats* keys are required. Their respective values are equal-length lists "
"with the field names and the field formats. The field names must be strings "
"and the field formats can be any object accepted by :class:`dtype` "
"constructor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:390
msgid ""
"When the optional keys *offsets* and *titles* are provided, their values "
"must each be lists of the same length as the *names* and *formats* lists. "
"The *offsets* value is a list of byte offsets (limited to `ctypes.c_int`) "
"for each field, while the *titles* value is a list of titles for each field "
"(``None`` can be used if no title is desired for that field). The *titles* "
"can be any object, but when a :class:`str` object will add another entry to "
"the fields dictionary keyed by the title and referencing the same field "
"tuple which will contain the title as an additional tuple member."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:401
msgid ""
"The *itemsize* key allows the total size of the dtype to be set, and must be "
"an integer large enough so all the fields are within the dtype. If the dtype "
"being constructed is aligned, the *itemsize* must also be divisible by the "
"struct alignment. Total dtype *itemsize* is limited to `ctypes.c_int`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:409
msgid ""
"Data type with fields ``r``, ``g``, ``b``, ``a``, each being an 8-bit "
"unsigned integer:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:415
msgid ""
"Data type with fields ``r`` and ``b`` (with the given titles), both being 8-"
"bit unsigned integers, the first at byte position 0 from the start of the "
"field and the second at position 2:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:443
msgid "``{'field1': ..., 'field2': ..., ...}``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:425
msgid ""
"This usage is discouraged, because it is ambiguous with the other dict-based "
"construction method. If you have a field called 'names' and a field called "
"'formats' there will be a conflict."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:430
msgid ""
"This style allows passing in the :attr:`fields <dtype.fields>` attribute of "
"a data-type object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:433
msgid ""
"*obj* should contain string or unicode keys that refer to ``(data-type, "
"offset)`` or ``(data-type, offset, title)`` tuples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:438
msgid ""
"Data type containing field ``col1`` (10-character string at byte position "
"0), ``col2`` (32-bit float at byte position 10), and ``col3`` (integers at "
"byte position 14):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:475
msgid "``(base_dtype, new_dtype)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:446
msgid ""
"In NumPy 1.7 and later, this form allows `base_dtype` to be interpreted as a "
"structured dtype. Arrays created with this dtype will have underlying dtype "
"`base_dtype` but will have fields and flags taken from `new_dtype`. This is "
"useful for creating custom structured dtypes, as done in :ref:`record arrays "
"<arrays.classes.rec>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:452
msgid ""
"This form also makes it possible to specify struct dtypes with overlapping "
"fields, functioning like the 'union' type in C. This usage is discouraged, "
"however, and the union mechanism is preferred."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.dtypes.rst:456
msgid ""
"Both arguments must be convertible to data-type objects with the same total "
"size."
msgstr ""

